<body class="ignore-math"><article class="exercise exercise-like"><article class="task exercise-like"><h4 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(a)</span></h4>
<p>Redo the integration by parts on the integral <span class="process-math">\(\int
x\cos(x)\dx{x}\)</span>  letting <span class="process-math">\(u=x\)</span> and <span class="process-math">\(\dx{v}=\cos(x)\dx{x}\)</span> as before. But suppose this time we take <span class="process-math">\(y=\sin(x)+a\)</span> where <span class="process-math">\(a\)</span> is an arbitrary constant. Show that we will obtain the same answer as before.</p>
<article class="task exercise-like"><h5 class="heading"><span class="codenumber">(a)</span></h5>
<p>Show that in general, if we let <span class="process-math">\(\int\dx{v}=v+a\)</span>  in the integration by parts formula, then we will obtain the same result as before, namely <span class="process-math">\(\int u\dx{v}=uv-\int v\dx{u}\text{.}\)</span></p></article></article></article></body>
